{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8d3b28e7e35db63a", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tQwen-Music Technical Report\n2\tReport GitHub Issue\n3\t×\n4\tTitle:\n5\tContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\n6\tDescription:\n7\tSubmit without GitHub\n8\tSubmit in GitHub\n9\tarXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\n10\tLearn more\n11\t×\n12\tBack to arXiv\n13\tLicense: arXiv.org perpetual non-exclusive license\n14\tarXiv:2607.11699v1 [cs.SD] 13 Jul 2026\n15\tQwen-Music Technical Report\n16\tQwen Team\n17\tAbstract\n18\tIn this report, we introduce Qwen-Music, a powerful music generation model capable of producing highly musical and high-fidelity songs with complete vocal singing.\n19\tQwen-Music supports two core tasks:  Text to Music Generation , which create entirely new songs from text descriptions, lyrics, and musical attributes, and  Cover Song Generation , which reinterprets existing songs with different styles and vocal characteristics.\n20\tArchitecturally, Qwen-Music integrates three core components:  Qwen-Music-Tokenizer ,  Qwen-Music-LLM , and  Qwen-Music-Render .\n21\tQwen-Music-Tokenizer compresses audio into a 25 Hz single-codebook stream of Music Semantic Tokens that preserve semantic and melodic information for LLM prediction.\n22\tBased on these tokens, Qwen-Music-LLM performs autoregressive music semantic modeling, with a key novelty being a melody-token-based chain-of-thought (Melody-CoT) mechanism that plans melodies before full-song generation, improving creativity, musicality, structural coherence, and reference-audio-based melody cloning.\n23\tTo overcome the fidelity limitations of discrete semantic tokens, Qwen-Music-Render performs generative stereo rendering, enriching acoustic details and producing high-fidelity stereo waveforms.\n24\tFinally, we train Qwen-Music-LLM on more than 5 million hours of multilingual music data covering hundreds of languages.\n25\tWe first apply quality-aware pre-training curriculum, then use progressive post-training, comprising supervised initialization, offline DPO, and online GSPO, to further improve musicality and instruction-following ability.\n26\tAcross 600 Chinese and English prompts, Qwen-Music achieves state-of-the-art results in 13 of 16 objective musicality and audio-quality metrics.\n27\tProfessional evaluators also prefer Qwen-Music over leading proprietary systems.\n28\tFor cover song generation, Qwen-Music preserves reference melodies more accurately than Suno V5.5, Suno V5, and MiniMax Cover on the AI-generated reference set, and outperforms MiniMax Cover on most metrics in the real-world popular-song reference set.\n29\tFigure 1:  Qwen-Music is a powerful and controllable music generation model capable of producing songs with complete vocal singing. It generates complete songs from text descriptions, lyrics, and musical attributes, and uses reference audio for cover song generation with different styles and vocal characteristics.\n30\t1  Introduction\n31\tMusic generation has recently emerged as a key challenge in generative modeling, aiming to synthesize music that is musically coherent, acoustically natural, and semantically aligned with user intent  (Agostinelli  et al. ,  2023 ; Schneider  et al. ,  2023 ; Copet  et al. ,  2024 ; Lam  et al. ,  2024 ; Majumder  et al. ,  2024 ; Huang  et al. ,  2023 ; Chen  et al. ,  2024 ) .\n32\tUnlike general audio generation, song generation requires the joint modeling of lyrics, melody, rhythm, vocal performance, instrumentation, and musical structure over minutes  (Yang  et al. ,  2026 ; Lei  et al. ,  2026b ;  a ; Liu  et al. ,  2025 ; Gong  et al. ,  2025 ;  2026 ; Yuan  et al. ,  2025 ; Ning  et al. ,  2025 ; Jiang  et al. ,  2025 ; Lei  et al. ,  2024 ) .\n33\tA useful system should support open-ended song generation from text descriptions and lyrics while allowing users to control musical attributes such as genre, mood, instrumentation, and vocal timbre.\n34\tIt should also reinterpret existing songs by preserving a reference melody while changing style or vocal characteristics.\n35\tDespite rapid progress in large-scale audio generation models, generating songs with stable melodic development, clear lyric articulation, realistic singing voices, and natural instrumental accompaniment remains challenging.\n36\tThe central technical challenge is the mismatch between semantic composition and acoustic rendering. At the semantic level, a model must plan lyrics, vocal melody, section structure, repetition, and stylistic progression over long horizons. At the acoustic level, it must render timbre, phase, stereo placement, and high-frequency detail at waveform resolution. Discrete-token language models provide a scalable interface for global sequence generation, but compressed tokens lose acoustic detail  (Xu  et al. ,  2025 ; Défossez  et al. ,  2022 ; Yang  et al. ,  2026 ) . Reference-guided cover song generation adds another constraint: the system must reuse the melody while allowing controllable changes to the arrangement, singing voice, and style.\n37\tIn this report, we introduce  Qwen-Music , a large-scale music generation system that separates song generation into semantic composition and acoustic rendering.\n38\tQwen-Music supports both text-to-music generation and reference-audio-based cover song generation within a single framework.\n39\tGiven text descriptions, lyrics, musical attributes, and optional reference audio, Qwen-Music can generate complete songs with controllable genre, mood, instrumentation, vocal timbre, and vocal gender.\n40\tTrained on over 5 million hours of multilingual music data, Qwen-Music generalizes strongly across diverse languages, genres, and musical styles.\n41\tFigure 2:  Blind A/B preference results between Qwen-Music and leading proprietary systems, including MiniMax Music 2.5+, MiniMax Music 2.6, Mureka V8, Suno V5, and Suno V5.5, judged by professional human raters. Each pair is evaluated under anonymized and randomized presentation, and values indicate the percentage of expert votes preferring each system.\n42\tQwen-Music is designed around four key principles:\n43\t•\n44\tComposition in a compact semantic music space.  Instead of directly modeling waveforms, Qwen-Music represents music as 25 Hz single-codebook Music Semantic Tokens. This compact stream gives the autoregressive model a tractable sequence space for full-song composition while preserving the musical semantics needed by the renderer.\n45\t•\n46\tExplicit melody planning and control.  To bridge the gap between high-level textual intent and concrete musical realization, Qwen-Music-LLM makes melody an explicit intermediate representation. For text-to-music generation, Melody-CoT plans the vocal melody before full-token generation. For cover generation, reference melody tokens condition the sequence so the output follows the source melody under the new style and vocal attributes.\n47\t•\n48\tGenerative acoustic rendering.  Qwen-Music-Render treats Music Semantic Tokens as musical sketches for generative rendering. A semantic-conditioned DiT predicts acoustic latents, the Spec-VAE decoder reconstructs spectrograms, and the Band-Mode Refiner corrects frequency-dependent magnitude and phase detail before waveform synthesis.\n49\t•\n50\tQuality-graded scaling and multi-stage preference alignment.\n51\tTo effectively exploit large-scale heterogeneous music corpora, Qwen-Music organizes pre-training around a quality-graded data curriculum, progressively learning from data at different quality levels.\n52\tIt further adopts a multi-stage post-training pipeline that combines supervised learning, offline preference optimization, and online policy optimization to improve musicality, instruction following, and controllability.\n53\tEmpirically, Qwen-Music demonstrates strong competitiveness against leading proprietary music generation systems.\n54\tAs shown in Figure   2  , blind A/B preference tests judged by professional human raters show that Qwen-Music achieves win rates of 59.1% against MiniMax Music 2.5+, 66.7% against MiniMax Music 2.6, 58.3% against Mureka V8, and 55.4% against Suno V5, while remaining comparable to Suno V5.5 with a slight preference advantage of 50.3%.\n55\tBeyond our internal evaluation, Qwen-Music also appears as  JazzCat  on the Artificial Analysis Music with Vocals Leaderboard  1    1  1  https://artificialanalysis.ai/music/leaderboard/vocals    , ranking third among leading English vocal music generation systems (Figure   3  ).\n56\tObjective evaluation in Section   4   further shows that Qwen-Music obtains the best result on 13 out of 16 text-to-music metrics across SongBench  (Wu  et al. ,  2026 ) , SongEval  (Yao  et al. ,  2025 ) , and AudioBox-Aesthetic  (Tjandra  et al. ,  2025 ) , while cover song generation results demonstrate strong reference-melody preservation, stylistic adaptation, and vocal controllability.\n57\tFigure 3:  External leaderboard result on the Artificial Analysis Music with Vocals Leaderboard. Qwen-Music participated as  JazzCat  and ranked among the leading English vocal music generation systems.\n58\tOverall, Qwen-Music provides a unified framework for controllable, high-fidelity, and structurally coherent music generation. It bridges semantic-level composition and waveform-level synthesis, enabling both open-ended song creation and reference-guided musical reinterpretation in a single, coherent system.\n59\t2  Architecture\n60\tFigure 4:\n61\tOverview of the Qwen-Music inference pipeline.\n62\tGiven a user request, Qwen-Music first rewrites the natural-language description into a structured textual condition, including musical tags (such as genre, singer characteristics, instrumental arrangement, etc.) and generated lyrics.\n63\tQwen-Music-LLM then generates Music Semantic Tokens, optionally using melody tokens extracted from a reference song for melody cloning.\n64\tFinally, Qwen-Music-Render takes both the rewritten textual condition and the generated Music Semantic Tokens as input and performs generative rendering to produce high-fidelity 48 kHz stereo waveforms.\n65\t2.1  Overview\n66\tAs shown in Figure   4  , Qwen-Music follows an inference pipeline that transforms a user request into a complete high-fidelity stereo song.\n67\tGiven a natural-language description, the system first rewrites it into a structured textual condition containing musical tags (such as genre, singer characteristics, instrumental arrangement, etc.) and generated lyrics.\n68\tConditioned on this rewritten text, Qwen-Music-LLM autoregressively predicts Music Semantic Tokens, optionally incorporating reference melody tokens via Melody-CoT conditioning for cover song generation.\n69\tQwen-Music-Render then takes both the rewritten textual condition and the generated Music Semantic Tokens as input and performs generative rendering to produce high-fidelity 48 kHz stereo waveforms.\n70\tThis pipeline is supported by three core components: Qwen-Music-Tokenizer, Qwen-Music-LLM, and Qwen-Music-Render.\n71\t•\n72\tQwen-Music-Tokenizer  maps raw music audio into 25 Hz Music Semantic Tokens using a Conformer-based encoder. It is trained with a four-stage recipe that combines self-supervised learning, causal adaptation, multi-task supervision, and vector quantization. The resulting token stream provides the discrete music representation used for language-model training and renderer conditioning.\n73\t•\n74\tQwen-Music-LLM  generates Music Semantic Tokens conditioned on text descriptions, lyrics, musical attributes, and optional melody tokens. For original song generation, it can first produce a Melody-CoT plan before generating the full Music Semantic Token sequence. For cover song generation, it uses melody tokens extracted from a reference song as conditioning context while following the target style and vocal attributes.\n75\t•\n76\tQwen-Music-Render  converts generated Music Semantic Tokens into 48 kHz stereo waveforms. It uses a semantic-conditioned Diffusion Transformer to predict continuous acoustic latents, a spectral-domain VAE decoder to reconstruct complex spectrograms, and a Band-Mode Refiner to correct frequency-dependent magnitude and phase details before inverse STFT synthesis.\n77\tIn the following sections, we first introduce Qwen-Music-Tokenizer and its multi-stage training recipe. We then describe Qwen-Music-LLM, including melody tokenization and melody-aware generation. Finally, we present Qwen-Music-Render, focusing on diffusion-based latent generation, spectral-domain decoding, and band-wise refinement.\n78\t2.2  Qwen-Music-Tokenizer\n79\tFigure 5:\n80\tOverview of Qwen-Music-Tokenizer. The tokenizer maps music waveforms to 25 Hz Music Semantic Tokens through BestRQ pretraining, causal adaptation, multi-task SFT, and VQ tokenizer training.\n81\tQwen-Music-Tokenizer is a low-bitrate discrete tokenizer that maps a\n82\traw music waveform into a single stream of 25 Hz Music Semantic Tokens. It uses a single backbone consisting of a convolutional frontend followed by a Conformer encoder  (Gulati  et al. ,  2020 ) . As illustrated in Figure   5  , we\n83\ttrain the backbone in  four  stages: (i) bidirectional self-supervised pretraining with BestRQ  (Chiu  et al. ,  2022 ) , (ii) causal adaptation of the pretrained encoder,\n84\t(iii) multi-task supervised fine-tuning (SFT) with lyric and spectral targets,\n85\tand (iv) VQ tokenizer training. The final stage inserts the VQ\n86\tbottleneck and trains the final tokenizer. Stages 2–4 are initialize from the\n87\tprevious checkpoint, while Stage 1 starts from random initialization. This\n88\trecipe first learns continuous music representations and then introduces causal\n89\tattention, supervision, and vector quantization. The deployed tokenizer keeps\n90\tthe causal encoder up to the VQ insertion point and produces the    25  25    Hz token\n91\tstream consumed by downstream autoregressive models.\n92\tTable   1\n93\tsummarizes the recipe.\n94\t2.2.1  Backbone Architecture\n95\tThe tokenizer takes raw music audio as input and encodes it into a compact low-frame-rate token sequence.\n96\tSpecifically, each audio clip is converted to a mono    24  24    kHz waveform and represented using log-Mel spectrogram features.\n97\tA lightweight convolutional frontend reduces the frame rate to    25  25    Hz, corresponding to one frame every    40  40    ms.\n98\tThe tokenizer backbone is a    24  24   -layer,    0.6  0.6   B-parameter Conformer  (Gulati  et al. ,  2020 ) , which is shared across all four training stages.\n99\tStarting from Stage 2, the backbone is converted to causal self-attention to match the downstream autoregressive modeling setting.\n100\tWhen encoding audio, the tokenizer is applied offline to the full clip and produces a compact    25  25    Hz token stream.\n101\t2.2.2  Stage 1: Bidirectional BestRQ Pretraining\n102\tWe begin with a self-supervised pretraining stage to build a general-purpose music representation from unlabeled audio.\n103\tThe encoder is trained  bidirectionally  with BestRQ  (Chiu  et al. ,  2022 ) , a masked-prediction objective whose targets are produced by a  frozen  random quantizer, removing the need for a separately learned target network.\n104\tRandom-projection targets\n105\tTarget codes are formed from the clean log-Mel spectrogram: a local context\n106\twindow is pooled with temporal stride    4  4    so that targets align with the    25  25    Hz\n107\tencoder frames, projected by a fixed random projection, and mapped to the nearest\n108\tentry of a fixed,     ℓ  2   \\ell_{2}   -normalized random codebook. The projection and\n109\tcodebook are randomly initialized and kept frozen throughout training, so no\n110\ttarget network is learned.\n111\tMasking and objective\n112\tWe apply time-domain span masking: the waveform is partitioned into    0.4  0.4    s\n113\tspans, each masked independently with probability    0.3  0.3    (guaranteeing at least\n114\tone span per sample), and masked spans are replaced with low-variance Gaussian\n115\tnoise. The encoder consumes the masked audio, and a lightweight prediction head\n116\tis trained to recover the frozen random-projection targets at masked frames under\n117\ta cross-entropy loss,\n118\tℒ  BestRQ   =    1   |  ℳ  |    ​    ∑   t  ∈  ℳ     CE  ⁡   (   p  ​   (   h  t   )    ,   q  ​   (   x  t   )    )       .   \\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{BestRQ}}=\\frac{1}{|\\mathcal{M}|}\\sum_{t\\in\\mathcal{M}}\\operatorname{CE}\\bigl(p(h_{t}),q(x_{t})\\bigr).\n119\t(1)\n120\twhere    ℳ  \\mathcal{M}    is the set of masked frames,     h  t   h_{t}    is the encoder output at\n121\tframe    t  t   ,     q  ​   (  ⋅  )    q(\\cdot)    the frozen random-projection quantizer, and     p  ​   (  ⋅  )    p(\\cdot)    the\n122\tprediction head.\n123\t2.2.3  Stage 2: Causal Adaptation\n124\tTo prevent the encoder from accessing future frames and to align its\n125\trepresentations with downstream autoregressive modeling, we restrict\n126\tself-attention to be causal. Rather than training a causal encoder from\n127\tscratch, we resume BestRQ pretraining from the Stage 1 checkpoint after\n128\tswitching self-attention from full bidirectional masking to causal\n129\t(left-context-only) masking, while leaving the pretraining objective otherwise\n130\tunchanged. This short adaptation stage converts the encoder to causal\n131\tself-attention at a small fraction of the Stage 1 cost, while preserving much\n132\tof the representation learned under the less constrained bidirectional regime.\n133\tAll subsequent stages inherit causal attention.\n134\t2.2.4  Stage 3: Multi-Task Supervised Fine-Tuning\n135\tBefore quantization, we use multi-task supervision to make the encoder representations more informative for both language and music.\n136\tIn particular, this stage encourages the future discrete codes to preserve lyrical content together with musical semantic attributes such as melody and harmony.\n137\tWe attach three lightweight heads to the    25  25    Hz\n138\tencoder outputs: (i) a linear  CTC head   (Graves  et al. ,  2006 )  that transcribes lyrics\n139\tover a multilingual subword vocabulary; (ii) a ConvNeXt\n140\tMel head  that upsamples the latents back to the    100  100    Hz,    128  128   -bin Mel\n141\tspectrogram; and (iii) a ConvNeXt  chroma head  predicting the    12  12   -bin\n142\tchroma feature. The objective combines the CTC loss with spectral-reconstruction\n143\tlosses on Mel and chroma, each a sum of a spectral-convergence term and a\n144\tmagnitude term,\n145\tℒ  SFT   =     λ  ctc   ​   ℒ  CTC    +    λ  mel   ​   ℒ  spec  mel    +    λ  chr   ​   ℒ  spec  chroma      ,    λ  ctc   =   λ  mel   =   λ  chr   =  1    .   \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{SFT}}=\\lambda_{\\text{ctc}}\\,\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{CTC}}+\\lambda_{\\text{mel}}\\,\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{spec}}^{\\text{mel}}+\\lambda_{\\text{chr}}\\,\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{spec}}^{\\text{chroma}},\\qquad\\lambda_{\\text{ctc}}\\!=\\!\\lambda_{\\text{mel}}\\!=\\!\\lambda_{\\text{chr}}\\!=\\!1.\n146\t(2)\n147\tInput masking is effectively disabled (     p  mask   =  0.01   p_{\\text{mask}}\\!=\\!0.01   ) so the model\n148\tsees near-clean audio, and training operates on full songs (up to    300  300    s, i.e.       ∼  7.5   {\\sim}7.5   k latent frames at    25  25    Hz) rather than fixed crops. We initialize from\n149\tthe Stage 2 checkpoint.\n150\t2.2.5  Stage 4: Vector-Quantized Tokenizer\n151\tThe final stage discretizes the encoder by inserting a single VQ bottleneck at\n152\tan intermediate layer of the    24  24   -layer Conformer stack. The activation at that\n153\tlayer is quantized, and the remaining upper layers and the SFT heads then operate\n154\ton the quantized stream, forcing the codes to retain the information required for\n155\tlyric transcription and spectral reconstruction.\n156\tQuantizer\n157\tWe insert a single VQ codebook of    32768  32768    entries under a cosine metric, trained\n158\twith a straight-through estimator and a commitment loss.\n159\tThe quantizer incorporates dedicated mechanisms that keep essentially the entire\n160\tcodebook active throughout training, so that codebook utilization reaches\n161\t99  %   +   99\\%+    and dead codes are virtually eliminated even at     2  15   2^{15}    entries; the\n162\tfull code space therefore contributes to the bitrate budget. A single codebook of\n163\tsize     2  15   2^{15}    at    25  25    Hz corresponds to    25  25    tokens/s and a bitrate of\n164\t375  375    bit/s.\n165\tSmooth insertion and staged unfreezing\n166\tInjecting a hard quantizer into a converged encoder is unstable, so we blend the\n167\tquantized and continuous paths through a scalar gate,\n168\th  out   =   h  +   α  ​   (    h  q   −  h   )      h_{\\text{out}}=h+\\alpha\\,(h_{q}-h)   , where    α  \\alpha    ramps linearly from   0\n169\tto    1  1    over an initial warmup. Concurrently, we first freeze the frontend and all\n170\tlayers up to and including the insertion point and train only the quantizer, the\n171\tupper layers, and the heads, then unfreeze the whole model. The loss is the SFT\n172\tobjective plus the VQ loss, with the CTC weight lowered to    0.5  0.5    (Mel, chroma, and\n173\tVQ weights    1.0  1.0   ). We initialize from the Stage 3 checkpoint.\n174\tTokenization.\n175\tAt inference, extracting codes requires only the frontend, the Conformer layers\n176\tup to the insertion point, and the quantizer; the post-VQ layers and all heads are\n177\tdiscarded. Each    40  40    ms frame maps to a single integer in     [  0  ,  32768  )   [0,32768)   , giving the\n178\t25  25    Hz token stream consumed by downstream models.\n179\tTable 1:  Overview of the four-stage training recipe for Qwen-Music-Tokenizer.\n180\tAll stages share the    0.6  0.6   B-parameter Conformer backbone (   24  24    layers,\n181\twidth    1024  1024   ,    16  16    heads,    25  25    Hz latents) and are initialized from the previous\n182\tcheckpoint.\n183\tStage\n184\tObjective\n185\tAttention\n186\tAudio length\n187\tInit. from\n188\t1\n189\tBestRQ masked prediction\n190\tbidirectional\n191\t30  30    s crop\n192\trandom\n193\t2\n194\tBestRQ (causal adaptation)\n195\tcausal\n196\t30  30    s crop\n197\tStage 1\n198\t3\n199\tCTC    +  +    Mel    +  +    chroma SFT\n200\tcausal\n201\tfull song (      ≤  300   \\leq\\!300    s)\n202\tStage 2\n203\t4\n204\tSFT    +  +    VQ\n205\tcausal\n206\tfull song (      ≤  300   \\leq\\!300    s)\n207\tStage 3\n208\t2.3  Qwen-Music-LLM\n209\tQwen-Music-LLM adopts an autoregressive backbone\n210\tinitialized from a    3  3   B dense variant of Qwen3.5-Omni  (Team,  2026 ) . It models music in the discrete\n211\tsemantic-token space produced by Qwen-Music-Tokenizer. Given the output of the\n212\tprompt rewriter, including global music tags and structured lyrics, the model\n213\tpredicts a sequence of Music Semantic Tokens that captures the long-range\n214\tcomposition, vocal phrasing, accompaniment, and section-level musical\n215\tdevelopment of the target song. These generated tokens are then passed to\n216\tQwen-Music-Render for high-fidelity waveform synthesis.\n217\tA central challenge in text-to-music generation is that text prompts typically\n218\tspecify style and lyrics only at a high level, without explicitly determining the\n219\tmelodic contour or compositional structure of the song. Directly predicting\n220\tfull-mixture Music Semantic Tokens from text therefore requires the model to learn composition\n221\tand arrangement simultaneously. To address this, we introduce  Melody-CoT , a melody-token-based chain-of-thought for explicit melody planning: before generating full-mixture Music Semantic Tokens, the model is\n222\ttrained to produce an intermediate sequence of melody tokens that describes a\n223\tcoarse-grained vocal melody contour. This intermediate melody plan encourages\n224\tthe LLM to first resolve the compositional structure of the song and then render\n225\tthat plan into the full Music Semantic Token sequence.\n226\tMelody-CoT also provides a unified interface for text-to-music and cover song\n227\tgeneration. For text-to-music generation, Qwen-Music-LLM conditions only on tags and\n228\tlyrics and directly generates Music Semantic Tokens, optionally producing the melody plan\n229\tas an intermediate step. For cover song generation, melody tokens extracted\n230\tfrom a reference song are inserted into the prefix together with the target tags\n231\tand lyrics. The model then generates new full-mixture Music Semantic Tokens that follow the\n232\treference melody contour while allowing timbre, arrangement, and genre to be\n233\tcontrolled by the textual conditions.\n234\t2.3.1  Melody Tokenizer\n235\tThe Melody Tokenizer converts a reference vocal pitch contour into a compact\n236\tsequence of discrete melody tokens. We first extract a    50  50    Hz vocal pitch curve\n237\tusing RMVPE  (Wei  et al. ,  2023 ) . Since the goal is to preserve the compositional melody rather than\n238\tfine-grained singing expression, the pitch curve is downsampled by a factor of\n239\t8  8    with median pooling, yielding a    6.25  6.25    Hz melody sequence. This low frame\n240\trate suppresses local ornaments, vibrato, and other performance-level details\n241\twhile retaining the coarse contour needed for melody conditioning.\n242\tTo prevent the melody condition from leaking\n243\tabsolute pitch range, key, or singer-dependent timbre information, we use a\n244\trelative  MIDI representation. Specifically, we convert the downsampled pitch values from Hertz to MIDI pitch values and then compute the median MIDI value\n245\tover all voiced frames in the sequence and subtract it from every voiced frame.\n246\tThe resulting relative semitone offsets are clipped to a fixed range and mapped\n247\tto a    256  256   -entry vocabulary, with one dedicated token reserved for unvoiced\n248\tframes. As a result, the melody tokens encode the shape of the vocal melody but\n249\tdiscard most absolute-register information, encouraging the generated song to\n250\tobey the target tags and lyrics for style, timbre, and arrangement.\n251\tWe also explored chromagram-based representations  (Copet  et al. ,  2024 ; Zhang  et al. ,  2026 )  for melody tokenization.\n252\tHowever, our preliminary experiments indicate that chromagrams often retain\n253\tsubstantial information beyond the leading melody, including residual background\n254\tand acoustic details of the arrangement. Such extra information can make the conditioning signal\n255\ttoo strong and reduce the model’s ability to follow the global music tags. We therefore\n256\tadopt pitch-contour-based melody tokens as a cleaner representation of the\n257\treference melody.\n258\tFormally, let     𝐟  =   (   f  1   ,  …  ,   f  T   )    \\mathbf{f}=(f_{1},\\ldots,f_{T})    denote the\n259\tRMVPE pitch curve at    50  50    Hz. We first apply     8  ×   8{\\times}    median-pooling\n260\tdownsampling,\n261\t𝐟  ~   =    MedianPool  8   ⁡   (  𝐟  )     ,   \\tilde{\\mathbf{f}}=\\operatorname{MedianPool}_{8}(\\mathbf{f}),\n262\t(3)\n263\twhere unvoiced frames are ignored when computing the median and a pooled frame\n264\tis set to   0   if the corresponding window is mostly unvoiced. The melody token\n265\tz  i   z_{i}    is then computed as\n266\tm  ¯   \\displaystyle\\bar{m}\n267\t=   median  ⁡   {    round  ⁡   (   hz2midi  ⁡   (    f  ~   i   )    )    ​   ∣    f  ~   i   >   ​  0   }     ,   \\displaystyle=\\operatorname{median}\\{\\operatorname{round}(\\operatorname{hz2midi}(\\tilde{f}_{i}))\\mid\\tilde{f}_{i}>0\\},\n268\t(4)\n269\tz  i   \\displaystyle z_{i}\n270\t=   {        clip  ⁡   (    round  ⁡   (   hz2midi  ⁡   (    f  ~   i   )    )    −   m  ¯    ,   −  127   ,   127  )    +  127   ,         f  ~   i   >  0   ,        255  ,         f  ~   i   =  0   ,        \\displaystyle=\n271\twhere      f  ~   i   \\tilde{f}_{i}    is the downsampled pitch value,     m  ¯   \\bar{m}    is the global voiced\n272\tMIDI median, and      z  i   ∈   [  0  ,  255  ]    z_{i}\\in[0,255]    is the final melody token.\n273\t2.3.2  Melody-CoT Training\n274\tQwen-Music-LLM is trained with a next-token prediction objective over sequences\n275\tthat may contain text tokens, melody tokens, and Music Semantic Tokens. The\n276\ttext portion, consisting of tags and lyrics, is used as conditioning context.\n277\tLoss is applied to both the Melody-CoT region and the final Music Semantic Token region,\n278\tso the model learns not only to generate realistic Music Semantic Tokens, but also to\n279\tconstruct an explicit melody plan from textual conditions.\n280\tWe mix multiple sequence patterns during training to support different inference\n281\trequirements within a single model. The plain text-to-music pattern is\n282\t[  text  ,   music  ​  semantic  ​  tokens   ]   ,   [\\mathrm{text},\\ \\mathrm{music\\ semantic\\ tokens}],\n283\twhere the model directly generates Music Semantic Tokens from tags and lyrics. The\n284\tmelody-planning patterns insert Melody-CoT before the Music Semantic Token sequence:\n285\t[  text  ,   section  ​  -  ​  level  ​  melody   ,   music  ​  semantic  ​  tokens   ]   [\\mathrm{text},\\ \\mathrm{section\\text{-}level\\ melody},\\ \\mathrm{music\\ semantic\\ tokens}]\n286\tand\n287\t[  text  ,   unique  ​  -  ​  section  ​  -  ​  level  ​  melody   ,   music  ​  semantic  ​  tokens   ]   .   [\\mathrm{text},\\ \\mathrm{unique\\text{-}section\\text{-}level\\ melody},\\ \\mathrm{music\\ semantic\\ tokens}].\n288\tBalancing these patterns allows the model to retain strong text-to-music\n289\tcapability while also learning to use explicit melody conditions for cover song\n290\tgeneration.\n291\tThe  section-level  Melody-CoT pattern writes melody tokens for vocal\n292\tsections that contain lyrics. Each melody segment is preceded by its section\n293\tlabel, such as  [verse]  or  [chorus] , and non-vocal sections\n294\tsuch as  intros ,  instrumental breaks ,  outros , and  silence  are omitted from the\n295\tMelody-CoT sequence. This design weakens the melody condition compared with a\n296\tfull-song pitch trace and avoids exposing the exact full-song duration through\n297\tthe length of the melody sequence.\n298\tThe  unique-section-level  pattern further reduces over-conditioning. Instead of\n299\tincluding every occurrence of a repeated section label, it groups candidate\n300\tsegments by section type and samples one representative melody segment for each\n301\tunique label during training. For example, multiple chorus occurrences are\n302\trepresented by one sampled chorus melody. This shortens the Melody-CoT sequence,\n303\timproves data diversity across epochs, and encourages the model to use melody as\n304\ta reusable compositional guide rather than copying the reference song frame by\n305\tframe.\n306\t2.4  Qwen-Music-Render\n307\tFigure 6:  Overview of Qwen-Music-Render. Music Semantic Tokens and text\n308\tconditions guide a semantic-conditioned DiT that predicts\n309\tacoustic latents. Spec-VAE decodes the latents into complex spectrograms,\n310\tand the Band-Mode Refiner corrects band-dependent magnitude and phase details\n311\tbefore inverse STFT synthesis to 48 kHz stereo waveforms.\n312\tThe language model captures long-range musical structure in a compact\n313\tdiscrete token space. We introduce  Qwen-Music-Render , a three-stage neural\n314\trender that turns this discrete output into a high-fidelity waveform.\n315\tThe first stage is a  Diffusion Transformer  (DiT)  (Peebles and Xie,  2023 ; Liu  et al. ,  2023 ; Lipman  et al. ,  2023 )  that, conditioned\n316\ton the discrete tokens together with the textual musical tags and lyrics, produces a continuous latent through conditional flow\n317\tmatching. The second stage is  Spec-VAE , whose Spec Decoder inverts\n318\tthe latent sequence back to a coarse complex STFT. The\n319\tthird stage is a  Band-Mode Refiner  that predicts\n320\tfrequency-adaptive magnitude and phase residuals on top of the decoder\n321\toutput; a final inverse STFT produces the 48 kHz stereo waveform.\n322\t2.4.1  Diffusion Transformer\n323\tThe Music Semantic Tokens generated by the language model provide a discrete representation of the song’s global structure, section ordering, and vocal/instrumental arrangement. Conditioned on these tokens, the Diffusion Transformer (DiT) predicts the latent representation, which is subsequently decoded by the downstream Spec Decoder into a listenable spectrogram.\n324\tArchitecture\n325\tOur backbone is a    1.3  1.3    B DiT operating on continuous latents. It comprises 32 Transformer blocks with hidden dimension     d  =  1024   d=1024   , 24 attention heads, and a feed-forward expansion ratio of 8. Rotary positional embeddings (RoPE)  (Su  et al. ,  2024 )  are applied to the queries and keys in self-attention. Each block consists of a self-attention layer, a cross-attention layer that attends to the auxiliary conditioning context described below, and a feed-forward layer, all modulated by AdaLN parameters derived from the diffusion timestep.\n326\tAt each forward pass, the network takes as input a noisy latent      ϕ  t   ∈   ℝ   T  ×  m     \\phi_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times m}    with     m  =  128   m=128   , together with a frame-aligned token sequence     𝐜  ∈    {  1  ,  …  ,  V  }   T    \\mathbf{c}\\in\\{1,\\ldots,V\\}^{T}    generated by the language model at 25 Hz.\n327\tConditioning\n328\tIn Qwen-Music-Render, we further provide the DiT with the rewritten textual condition produced by the prompt rewriter, in addition to the Music Semantic Tokens generated by Qwen-Music-LLM.\n329\tWe find that this additional textual conditioning improves audio quality and helps the renderer better follow the intended song specification.\n330\tSpecifically, we use a frozen Qwen3-Embedding-0.6B  (Zhang  et al. ,  2025 )  text encoder to extract features from the textual condition, and inject them into the DiT through cross-attention.\n331\tThe song-description tokens are projected to the DiT hidden width with a bias-free linear layer, while the lyric tokens are further processed by a 6-layer RoPE Transformer encoder trained jointly with the DiT.\n332\tThe resulting description and lyric representations are concatenated into a single cross-attention context    𝒞  \\mathcal{C}    attended by each DiT block.\n333\tTo enable classifier-free guidance (CFG) at inference time, we introduce a learnable null context     𝒞  ∅   \\mathcal{C}_{\\emptyset}    for the text-conditioning branch.\n334\tDuring CFG inference, the conditional pass uses both the Music Semantic Tokens and the full text context    𝒞  \\mathcal{C}   , while the unconditional pass keeps the Music Semantic Tokens unchanged and replaces    𝒞  \\mathcal{C}    with     𝒞  ∅   \\mathcal{C}_{\\emptyset}   .\n335\tTraining details\n336\tWe train the model in two stages. First, the DiT is pretrained on a large-scale music corpus. It is then supervised fine-tuned (SFT) on a smaller set of curated, lossless-quality recordings, which further improves output audio quality. Training samples are limited to tracks of up to 6 minutes, corresponding to at most 9,000 frames at 25 Hz. The cross-attention context is truncated to 256 tokens for the song description and 1536 tokens for the lyrics. We use AdamW for optimization, together with a linear warm-up schedule and gradient clipping at    1.0  1.0   .\n337\t2.4.2  Spec-VAE & Refiner\n338\tArchitecture\n339\tSpec-VAE follows the 2D-conv architecture of SpectroStream  (Li and others,  2025 ) , with discrete residual vector-quantized tokens replaced by a continuous spectral latent to match the latent diffusion framework in Section   2.4.1  .\n340\tStereo audio at 48 kHz is transformed by STFT into a complex spectrogram     𝐗  ∈   ℂ   2  ×  480  ×  T     \\mathbf{X}\\in\\mathbb{C}^{2\\times 480\\times T}   .\n341\tA 7-block Spec Encoder compresses the spectrogram into 128-dimensional latents at 25 Hz, achieving a total compression ratio of     192  ×   192\\times   , while a mirrored Spec Decoder reconstructs a coarse complex spectrogram for iSTFT synthesis.\n342\tStereo channels are handled with delayed fusion in the encoder and early splitting in the decoder.\n343\tTo further improve reconstruction quality, we attach a lightweight Band-Mode Refiner after the decoder to correct residual spectral artifacts.\n344\tFigure 7:  Spec-SnakeBeta analysis.\n345\t(a)  Activation curves: the standard SnakeBeta (black dashed)\n346\tapplies a single shared    α  \\alpha    to all frequency bins; Spec-SnakeBeta\n347\tadapts the periodic modulation per frequency, producing distinct\n348\tnonlinear shapes at 0.5, 3, 10, and 20 kHz.\n349\t(b)  Deviation of learned     α  f   \\alpha_{f}    from log-frequency\n350\tinitialization (     Δ  ​   α  f    =    α  learned   −   α  init     \\Delta\\alpha_{f}=\\alpha_{\\text{learned}}-\\alpha_{\\text{init}}   ) across encoder layers—positive values indicate\n351\tthe network increases periodic modulation beyond the physical prior,\n352\twith the strongest deviations concentrated in 0–5 kHz.\n353\tSpec-SnakeBeta\n354\tWe introduce  Spec-SnakeBeta , a frequency-aware extension of the SnakeBeta activation used in BigVGAN  (Lee  et al. ,  2023 ) .\n355\tWhile the original SnakeBeta uses channel-wise learnable parameters, Spec-SnakeBeta parameterizes    α  \\alpha    and    β  \\beta    along the frequency axis, exploiting the fact that each STFT bin corresponds to a fixed physical frequency:\n356\tSpec  -  SnakeBeta   ​    (  𝐱  )    b  ,  c  ,  t  ,  f     =    x   b  ,  c  ,  t  ,  f    +    1    exp  ⁡   (   β  f   )    +  ϵ    ​    sin  2   ⁡   (    x   b  ,  c  ,  t  ,  f    ⋅   exp  ⁡   (   α  f   )     )       .   \\text{Spec\\mbox{-}SnakeBeta}(\\mathbf{x})_{b,c,t,f}=x_{b,c,t,f}+\\frac{1}{\\exp(\\beta_{f})+\\epsilon}\\,\\sin^{2}\\left(x_{b,c,t,f}\\cdot\\exp(\\alpha_{f})\\right).\n357\t(5)\n358\tWe initialize     α  f   \\alpha_{f}    with a log-frequency prior,\n359\tα  f   =   log  ⁡   (     freq  f    f  ¯    +  ϵ   )     ,    f  ¯   =    1  F   ​    ∑  f    freq  f       ,   \\alpha_{f}=\\log\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{freq}_{f}}{\\bar{f}}+\\epsilon\\right),\\qquad\\bar{f}=\\frac{1}{F}\\sum_{f}\\mathrm{freq}_{f},\n360\t(6)\n361\twhich encourages stronger periodic modulation at higher frequencies.\n362\tAs shown in Figure   7  , the learned parameters preserve this frequency-dependent structure while adapting most strongly in the low-to-mid frequency range.\n363\tThis frequency-dependent parameterization provides the activation prior used by the Spec-VAE decoder.\n364\tBand-Mode Refiner\n365\tThe Band-Mode Refiner is a lightweight ConvNeXt-1D module  (Liu  et al. ,  2022 )  that refines the decoder’s complex spectrogram output.\n366\tMotivated by the complementary error patterns of magnitude and phase across frequency bands, it applies band-specific corrections:\n367\tphase-only correction in the low-frequency band, joint magnitude and phase correction in the mid-frequency band, and magnitude-only correction in the high-frequency band.\n368\tThis design improves spectral fidelity while preserving stable optimization: at initialization, all refiner weights are zero, so the refined output is exactly equal to the decoder output.\n369\tTraining Objective and Discriminators\n370\tThe decoder system is trained with a combination of multi-resolution STFT loss  (Yamamoto  et al. ,  2020 ) , IF/GD phase loss  (Wang and others,  2025 ) , LSGAN adversarial loss with feature matching  (Mao  et al. ,  2017 ; Larsen  et al. ,  2016 ) , and KL regularization.\n371\tWe further adopt K-weighting perceptual filtering  (ITU-R,  2015 ) , MSLR stereo decomposition  (Wang and others,  2025 ) , adaptive log-magnitude normalization from SAME  (Liao and others,  2025 ) , and mixed-scale spectral losses from SpectroStream  (Li and others,  2025 ) .\n372\tFor adversarial training, we use complementary STFT, CQT, and spectral-domain discriminators to provide both waveform-level and spectral-domain feedback.\n373\tThree-Stage Training Pipeline\n374\tAs summarized in Table   2  , training proceeds in three stages.\n375\tStage 1 performs reconstruction-only Spec-VAE pretraining.\n376\tStage 2 introduces waveform-domain adversarial training.\n377\tStage 3 freezes the Spec-VAE encoder–decoder and trains the Band-Mode Refiner with both waveform and spectral discriminators.\n378\tThis staged recipe stabilizes training under the     192  ×   192\\times    compression setting and progressively improves fine-grained acoustic detail.\n379\tTable 2:  Spec-VAE and refiner training configuration across three stages.\n380\tStage 1 is reconstruction-only pretraining.\n381\tStage 2 introduces waveform-domain adversarial training.\n382\tStage 3 freezes the encoder–decoder and trains the refiner with\n383\twaveform ( W ) and spectral ( S ) discriminators.\n384\tCategory\n385\tParam\n386\tStage 1\n387\tStage 2\n388\tStage 3\n389\tOptimizer\n390\tGenerator optim.\n391\tMuon\n392\tMuon\n393\tAdamW\n394\tGenerator LR\n395\t10   −  4    10^{-4}\n396\t1.5  ×   10   −  4     1.5\\times 10^{-4}\n397\t1.5  ×   10   −  4     1.5\\times 10^{-4}\n398\tDisc optim\n399\t—\n400\tMuon\n401\tAdamW\n402\tDisc LR\n403\t—\n404\t3  ×   10   −  5     3\\times 10^{-5}\n405\t10   −  6    10^{-6}    (W) /     10   −  5    10^{-5}    (S)\n406\tSchedule\n407\tBatch size / GPU\n408\t4\n409\t1\n410\t1\n411\tSegment length\n412\t1.28 s\n413\t1.28 s\n414\t1.28 s\n415\tDisc warmup step\n416\t—\n417\t0\n418\t0 (W) / 15k (S)\n419\tG​:​D interleave\n420\t—\n421\t1​:​1\n422\t4​:​1\n423\tArchitecture\n424\tSTFT disc scales\n425\t—\n426\t8\n427\t8\n428\tCQT disc\n429\t✗\n430\t✓\n431\t✓\n432\tSpectral disc\n433\t✗\n434\t✗\n435\t✓\n436\tLoss weights\n437\tλ  STFT   \\lambda_{\\text{STFT}}\n438\t1.0\n439\t1.0\n440\t0.5\n441\tλ  IF_GD   \\lambda_{\\text{IF\\_GD}}\n442\t0\n443\t0\n444\t0.1\n445\tλ  KL   \\lambda_{\\text{KL}}\n446\t10   −  6    10^{-6}\n447\t10   −  6    10^{-6}\n448\t0\n449\tλ  time-GAN   ​   (     A  ​  d  ​  v   /  F   ​  M   )    \\lambda_{\\text{time-GAN}}\\penalty 10000\\ (Adv/FM)\n450\t—\n451\t1.0 / 100\n452\t0.175 / 20\n453\tλ  spec-GAN   ​   (     A  ​  d  ​  v   /  F   ​  M   )    \\lambda_{\\text{spec-GAN}}\\penalty 10000\\ (Adv/FM)\n454\t—\n455\t—\n456\t0.5 / 35\n457\t2.4.3  Acoustic Data Quality Pipeline\n458\tWe train Qwen-Music-Render only on files whose acoustic evidence matches a\n459\tgenuine high-fidelity music target. Raw collections often contain lossless\n460\tcontainers transcoded from MP3, duplicated-mono “stereo” tracks, clipped or\n461\tover-limited masters, and upsampled files whose high-frequency band is empty.\n462\tWe therefore apply the automated pipeline\n463\tsummarized in Table   3   before renderer training and\n464\tevaluation.\n465\tTable 3:  Metric-level checklist used by the acoustic pipeline.\n466\tEach row pairs a rule-engine identifier with a brief description\n467\tand its pass/flag condition.\n468\tCheck\n469\tMetric ID\n470\tEvidence\n471\tCondition\n472\tMeta & encoder\n473\tencoder_tag\n474\tEncoder string in container/stream tags\n475\tflag if  lavf/lavc/ffmpeg/lame\n476\tmutagen_tags\n477\tMetadata sweep for conversion traces\n478\tflag if  transcode/convert\n479\tBitrate\n480\thas_non_monotonic_pts\n481\tPTS monotonicity\n482\tpass if  false\n483\tbitrate_utilization\n484\tRealized / nominal bitrate\n485\tpass if       ≥  0.6   \\geq 0.6\n486\ttop10_bitrate_mean\n487\tComplex-segment mean bitrate\n488\tpass if     ≥  1.2  ×   \\geq 1.2\\times    mean\n489\tvbr_variation\n490\tBitrate coefficient of variation\n491\tpass if      σ  /  μ   ≥  0.15   \\sigma/\\mu\\geq 0.15\n492\tquality_tier\n493\tBitrate-based quality level\n494\tHiRes/High/Med/Low/Trash\n495\tLoudness\n496\tlufs_i\n497\tIntegrated loudness (EBU R128)\n498\t[   −  25   ,   −  5   ]   [-25,-5]    LUFS\n499\ttrue_peak\n500\tdBTP level\n501\t[   −  1   ,   +  2   ]   [-1,+2]    dBFS\n502\tlra\n503\tLoudness range\n504\t[  3  ,  15  ]   [3,15]    LU\n505\tplr\n506\tPeak-to-loudness ratio\n507\t≥  6   \\geq 6    LU\n508\tFake stereo\n509\tlr_diff_zero_ratio\n510\tFraction of zero     |   L  −  R   |   |L-R|    samples\n511\tpass if       <  0.99   <0.99\n512\tFreq cutoff\n513\tcutoff_ratio\n514\tCutoff / Nyquist freq ratio\n515\tranking from     0.5  →  1.0   0.5\\to 1.0\n516\tdrop_db\n517\tEnergy gap around     f  c   f_{c}\n518\thard       ≥  40   \\geq 40    dB; suspicious       ≥  20   \\geq 20    dB\n519\tvalid_segments\n520\tNon-silent interior FFT windows\n521\tpass if       >  0   >0\n522\tNoise-floor-aware cutoff detection\n523\tContainer metadata alone cannot distinguish true high-resolution content from\n524\tan upsampled or lossy-transcoded file. The key idea is to estimate the noise\n525\tfloor from track  edges  and detect the spectral cutoff from\n526\tinterior  segments, keeping the two estimates independent.\n527\tWe reserve the first and last 10% of the mono waveform as edge segments and\n528\tcompute Hann-windowed    8192  8192   -point RFFTs over non-overlapping windows. After\n529\tpeak-normalizing and averaging their magnitude spectra, the empirical noise\n530\tfloor is\n531\tη  ^   =   20  ​    log  10   ⁡   (   median  ​   (     𝐌  ¯   edge   ​   [  top 10% bins  ]    )    )      .   \\hat{\\eta}=20\\log_{10}\\bigl(\\mathrm{median}(\\bar{\\mathbf{M}}_{\\mathrm{edge}}[\\text{top 10\\% bins}])\\bigr).\n532\t(7)\n533\tFor the cutoff, we process five equally spaced interior windows that skip\n534\tnear-silent regions and average the resulting spectra. The detected cutoff\n535\tf  c   f_{c}    is the highest FFT bin whose mean magnitude remains above     −  80   -80    dB\n536\trelative to the peak. We then measure a local energy drop across a     ±  2   \\pm 2    kHz\n537\tband around     f  c   f_{c}   :\n538\tΔ  dB   =  max    𝐌  ¯   int    [   f  c   −  2  kHz  :   f  c   ]   −  max    𝐌  ¯   int    [   f  c   :   f  c   +  2  kHz  ]   ,   \\Delta_{\\mathrm{dB}}=\\max\\bar{\\mathbf{M}}_{\\mathrm{int}}[f_{c}{-}2\\,\\text{kHz}:f_{c}]-\\max\\bar{\\mathbf{M}}_{\\mathrm{int}}[f_{c}:f_{c}{+}2\\,\\text{kHz}],\n539\t(8)\n540\twhere the computation replaces the post-cutoff maximum with     η  ^   \\hat{\\eta}    when no\n541\treliable content exists above     f  c   f_{c}   . The final label depends on both the cutoff\n542\tratio      f  c   /   f  Nyq    f_{c}/f_{\\mathrm{Nyq}}    and the drop magnitude. The rule marks a file as\n543\thard_cutoff  when the ratio falls below    0.85  0.85    and the drop reaches\n544\tΔ  dB   ≥  40   \\Delta_{\\mathrm{dB}}\\geq 40    dB, or       ≥  25   \\geq 25    dB near     η  ^   \\hat{\\eta}   . It marks a\n545\tfile as  suspicious  when the ratio is below    0.90  0.90    with\n546\tΔ  dB   ≥  20   \\Delta_{\\mathrm{dB}}\\geq 20    dB. Files that meet neither condition are labeled\n547\tnatural .\n548\tFigure 8:  High-frequency cutoff detector examples. The blue\n549\tcurve is the Welch spectrum of a 10 s verification segment, the red dashed\n550\tline is the detected cutoff     f  c   f_{c}   , and the gray dotted line is the independently\n551\testimated edge noise floor.\n552\tFigure   8   visualizes four representative\n553\toutcomes. The first two panels show classic lossy-to-lossless signatures: a\n554\tsharp wall well below Nyquist and post-cutoff energy collapsed to the noise\n555\tfloor. The last two panels are closer to Nyquist and therefore require the\n556\tnoise-floor-aware drop test; the detector flags them only when the roll-off is\n557\tboth low enough in frequency and steep enough in level.\n558\t3  Training\n559\tThe remaining training pipeline targets Qwen-Music-LLM. Renderer-specific\n560\tacoustic filtering appears in Section   2.4.3  ; here we train\n561\tthe backbone LLM through quality-aware pre-training and progressive\n562\tpost-training.\n563\t3.1  Quality-Graded Pre-training Curriculum\n564\tTo effectively exploit large-scale music corpora with heterogeneous quality distributions, Qwen-Music adopts a quality-graded pre-training curriculum for the backbone LLM.\n565\tInstead of simply discarding all lower-quality data, we organize the corpus into quality levels and schedule them progressively, allowing the model to first learn broad musical coverage and then concentrate on higher-quality generation.\n566\tFollowing the multi-aspect song-quality assessment protocols of SongBench  (Wu  et al. ,  2026 )  and SongEval  (Yao  et al. ,  2025 ) , we train an internal MOS-based reward model.\n567\tThis model is trained on data annotated by human raters with professional music backgrounds, and its predicted scores are used to estimate and rank the general musical quality of each audio sample.\n568\tWithin each genre, we rank samples and partition them into seven quality buckets (Q1–Q7)\n569\tusing percentile thresholds at 90%, 75%, 50%, 25%, 5%, and 1%. Q1 denotes the\n570\thighest-quality bucket, and Q7 denotes the\n571\tlowest-quality bucket. This genre-normalized stratification reduces bias toward\n572\tdominant styles and balances quality modeling across musical categories. We\n573\tremove Q7 and use the remaining Q1–Q6 subsets for model training.\n574\tAs described in Section   2.3  , Qwen-Music-LLM is initialized from a    3  3   B dense variant of Qwen3.5-Omni  (Team,  2026 ) , whose language-model backbone provides useful prior knowledge of language and music.\n575\tWe then train the model with a three-stage curriculum that gradually moves from broad data coverage to high-quality refinement.\n576\tStage 1: General pre-training\n577\tIn the first stage, we train on Q3–Q6 data, which accounts for the majority of the over 5 million-hour corpus.\n578\tThe objective is to learn a general mapping from text conditions, including lyrics and musical tags, to music semantic tokens.\n579\tTo improve both robustness and generation quality, we use a dynamic quality sampling strategy in which lower-quality data is emphasized early in training and gradually replaced by higher-quality data as training progresses.\n580\tWe further apply language balancing to mitigate cross-lingual data imbalance and include 20% instrumental music to strengthen accompaniment modeling.\n581\tStage 2: Annealing\n582\tIn the second stage, we train on Q2-level data with a learning-rate decay schedule.\n583\tThis stage serves as a quality consolidation phase, helping the model transition from broad data coverage to more structured and stable music generation.\n584\tIt improves musical structure, coherence, and overall audio quality while reducing artifacts introduced by noisier data in the first stage.\n585\tStage 3: High-quality refinement\n586\tIn the final stage, we focus on Q1 data and additionally incorporate carefully selected high-quality samples from the full corpus.\n587\tThis stage further improves musicality, controllability, and instruction following.\n588\tWe maintain balanced genre and language distributions to avoid overfitting to dominant styles and to ensure stable generation under diverse control conditions.\n589\t3.2  Multi-Stage Post-training Alignment\n590\tAfter pre-training, we further align Qwen-Music-LLM with human musical preferences and user instructions through a multi-stage post-training pipeline.\n591\tThe pipeline optimizes two complementary objectives: improving musicality, measured by the internal musicality MOS predictor described above, and enhancing instruction following, including genre control and lyric following, with rewards computed by Qwen3.5-Omni  (Team,  2026 )  and Qwen3-ASR  (Shi  et al. ,  2026 ) .\n592\tWe organize post-training from stable to exploratory: supervised learning first establishes a clean generation prior, offline preference optimization then improves alignment in a controlled manner, and online policy optimization finally unlocks further gains in musicality and audio quality.\n593\tPhase I: Supervised Cold Start\n594\tWe first perform supervised fine-tuning on carefully curated high-quality data.\n595\tThis stage selects samples that are both aligned with human preference and reliably annotated with control information, especially genre tags and lyrics.\n596\tBy emphasizing high-quality music examples with accurate style labels and lyric annotations, the model establishes a clean generation prior with strong controllability before reward-based optimization begins.\n597\tPhase II: Iterative Offline Preference Alignment\n598\tBuilding on the SFT model, we perform iterative offline alignment with Direct Preference Optimization (DPO)  (Rafailov  et al. ,  2023 ) .\n599\tIn each iteration, the current policy generates rollouts under diverse prompts and control conditions, and the musicality MOS predictor together with instruction-following reward models score these outputs.\n600\tWe then construct preference pairs from the scored candidates and optimize Qwen-Music-LLM with DPO.\n601\tRepeating this rollout–rewarding–pair construction–optimization loop progressively improves musicality and controllability while producing a policy that is more stable and better aligned for subsequent online optimization.\n602\tPhase III: Online Musicality Optimization\n603\tFinally, we apply on-policy Group Sequence Policy Optimization (GSPO)  (Zheng  et al. ,  2025 ) .\n604\tCompared with offline DPO, GSPO enables stronger exploration by updating the policy directly from on-policy samples and sequence-level rewards.\n605\tBecause the model has already acquired reliable generation ability and instruction-following behavior in the first two phases, this stage can focus on fine-grained musicality and audio-quality improvement rather than correcting fundamental alignment issues.\n606\tTogether, these three phases provide a stable optimization path for Qwen-Music-LLM, yielding stronger musicality, better controllability, and more reliable instruction following.\n607\t4  Evaluation\n608\tQwen-Music is evaluated on two core tasks: text-to-music generation and cover song generation.\n609\tIn blind A/B preference tests conducted by professional human raters (Figure   2  ), Qwen-Music outperforms MiniMax Music 2.6, MiniMax Music 2.5+, Mureka V8, and Suno V5, while remaining competitive with Suno V5.5.\n610\tGenre-wise Bradley–Terry analysis further shows strong preference across diverse musical styles (Table   4  ), and the Artificial Analysis leaderboard provides an external reference point for its performance among leading English vocal music generation systems (Figure   3  ).\n611\tBeyond full-song generation, we also evaluate Qwen-Music-Render through generative rendering ablations, acoustic reconstruction benchmarks, and refiner-specific analyses.\n612\tTogether, these evaluations show that Qwen-Music combines strong musicality, controllability, lyric intelligibility, cover-song melody preservation, and high-fidelity stereo rendering.\n613\t4.1  Evaluation of Music Generation\n614\tWe evaluate Qwen-Music on two music generation tasks:  text-to-music generation  and  cover song generation .\n615\tText-to-music generation measures the ability to create complete songs from a user’s natural-language prompt or request.\n616\tCover song generation measures the ability to reinterpret a reference song or melody according to the user’s desired target style and vocal direction.\n617\tBaseline Systems\n618\tFor text-to-music generation, we compare Qwen-Music against five state-of-the-art proprietary music generation systems: Suno V5.5, Suno V5, Mureka V8, MiniMax Music 2.6, and MiniMax Music 2.5+.\n619\tFor cover song generation, we retain the leading proprietary services that support this capability: Suno V5.5, Suno V5, and MiniMax Cover.\n620\tSince the Suno systems do not accept real-world songs as reference inputs, comparisons with Suno are limited to the AI-generated reference set.\n621\tEvaluation Metrics\n622\tWe use complementary objective metrics to evaluate musicality, audio quality, controllability, intelligibility, and melody preservation.\n623\tFor general musical quality, SongBench  Wu  et al.  ( 2026 )  scores melody, arrangement, musicality, vocal quality, instrumental quality, mixing, and structure, with higher values indicating better performance.\n624\tFor text-to-music generation, we also report SongEval  Yao  et al.  ( 2025 )  and AudioBox-Aesthetic  Tjandra  et al.  ( 2025 )  as additional music-aesthetic evaluation frameworks.\n625\tFor lyric intelligibility and lyric following, Qwen3-ASR  (Shi  et al. ,  2026 )  transcribes the generated audio and we compute the Phoneme Error Rate (PER) against the input lyrics; lower PER is better, and we report PER after multiplying by 100.\n626\tFor tag following, Gemini 3.1 Pro  Comanici  et al.  ( 2025 )  rates each generated song on a 1–10 scale across genre, mood, instrument, vocal gender, and vocal timbre, where higher scores indicate better adherence to the target musical tags.\n627\tFor cover song generation, we further measure reference-melody preservation using Melody MAE.\n628\tSpecifically, we convert both the generated cover and the reference song into relative MIDI representations following Eq.   4   in Section   2  , align the two melody sequences with dynamic time warping, and compute the mean absolute error in semitones.\n629\tLower Melody MAE indicates stronger preservation of the reference melody.\n630\t4.1.1  Text-to-Music Generation\n631\tTable 4:\n632\tGenre-wise Bradley–Terry ratings from blind A/B preference tests conducted by professional human raters.\n633\tRatings are computed independently within each genre and should be interpreted only for within-genre comparison.\n634\tHigher ratings indicate stronger preference.\n635\tBest results are highlighted in  bold , and second-best results are  underlined .\n636\tGenre\n637\tQwen-Music\n638\tSuno V5.5\n639\tSuno V5\n640\tMureka V8\n641\tMinimax\n642\tMusic 2.6\n643\tMinimax\n644\tMusic 2.5+\n645\tElectronic / EDM\n646\t1140\n647\t880\n648\t853\n649\t938\n650\t759\n651\t866\n652\tHip-Hop / Rap\n653\t1020\n654\t1205\n655\t1018\n656\t898\n657\t866\n658\t930\n659\tJazz & Blues\n660\t1112\n661\t961\n662\t968\n663\t202\n664\t868\n665\t930\n666\tMetal & Hard Rock\n667\t1039\n668\t880\n669\t1058\n670\t1070\n671\t859\n672\t942\n673\tPop\n674\t1020\n675\t1000\n676\t980\n677\t1050\n678\t977\n679\t880\n680\tPunk & Hardcore\n681\t1147\n682\t863\n683\t759\n684\t918\n685\t1120\n686\t202\n687\tR&B / Soul\n688\t1056\n689\t1032\n690\t950\n691\t1000\n692\t853\n693\t880\n694\tRock\n695\t1116\n696\t859\n697\t782\n698\t961\n699\t720\n700\t1027\n701\tSubjective Evaluation\n702\tTo complement the automatic evaluation, we conduct a blind A/B preference test between Qwen-Music and competing systems, with judgments collected from professional human raters.\n703\tWe use the same generated audio samples as in the objective evaluation.\n704\tFor each prompt and each comparison system, the audio generated by Qwen-Music and the corresponding baseline are paired and presented in random order.\n705\tA total of 50 professional human raters with music creation or production experience are recruited.\n706\tIn each trial, raters listen to two anonymized audio samples without knowing their model identities or generation sources, and select the one they prefer based on overall listening experience.\n707\tTo reduce positional bias, the order of the two samples is randomized for each trial.\n708\tEach A/B pair is independently judged by three different experts, and final preference rates are aggregated over all expert votes.\n709\tAs shown in Figure   2  , Qwen-Music is preferred over all comparison systems on average.\n710\tIt achieves a 59.1% win rate against MiniMax Music 2.5+, 66.7% against MiniMax Music 2.6, 58.3% against Mureka V8, and 55.4% against Suno V5.\n711\tThe closest comparison is against Suno V5.5, where Qwen-Music still obtains a slight preference advantage of 50.3% versus 49.7%, indicating comparable subjective quality to this strong commercial baseline.\n712\tTo further analyze robustness across musical styles, we group the test samples according to their genre tags and compute genre-wise Bradley–Terry ratings from the A/B preference outcomes.\n713\tRatings are estimated independently within each genre based on pairwise outcomes between Qwen-Music and each comparison system, and therefore should not be compared across different genres.\n714\tAs shown in Table   4  , Qwen-Music achieves the highest Bradley–Terry rating in five out of eight genres, including Electronic/EDM, Jazz & Blues, Punk & Hardcore, R&B/Soul, and Rock.\n715\tIt also ranks second in Hip-Hop/Rap and Pop, and remains competitive in Metal & Hard Rock.\n716\tThese results suggest that Qwen-Music maintains strong subjective preference across diverse musical styles, rather than showing advantages only in a narrow set of genres.\n717\tFigure   3   provides an additional external leaderboard reference.\n718\tOn the Artificial Analysis Music with Vocals Leaderboard, Qwen-Music participates as  JazzCat  and ranks in the top tier, reaching third place among leading English vocal music generation systems as shown in the figure.\n719\tTogether with the professional-rater A/B preference test and genre-wise Bradley–Terry analysis, this result further supports the strong and stable perceptual quality of Qwen-Music.\n720\tObjective Evaluation\n721\tAs shown in Table   5  , we conduct a comprehensive objective evaluation on a test set containing 300 Chinese and 300 English samples.\n722\tTo ensure a fair comparison, all systems are evaluated under identical input conditions, using AI-generated lyrics and musical tags with a balanced distribution across genres.\n723\tTable 5:  Objective text-to-music generation results on a bilingual test set containing 300 Chinese and 300 English examples.\n724\tMusicality and audio quality are evaluated using SongBench, SongEval, and AudioBox-Aesthetic.\n725\tTag following is evaluated by Gemini 3.1 Pro.\n726\tHigher is better except for PER.\n727\tBest results are shown in  bold , and second-best results are  underlined .\n728\tMetrics\n729\tQwen-Music\n730\tSuno V5.5\n731\tSuno V5\n732\tMureka V8\n733\tMinimax\n734\tMusic 2.6\n735\tMinimax\n736\tMusic 2.5+\n737\tSongBench\n738\tMelody\n739\t7.03\n740\t6.70\n741\t7.01\n742\t6.98\n743\t6.64\n744\t6.41\n745\tArrangement\n746\t7.35\n747\t7.03\n748\t7.20\n749\t7.14\n750\t6.72\n751\t6.45\n752\tMusicality\n753\t6.22\n754\t5.83\n755\t6.12\n756\t6.05\n757\t5.67\n758\t5.50\n759\tVocal\n760\t7.44\n761\t6.95\n762\t7.37\n763\t7.38\n764\t6.99\n765\t6.89\n766\tInstrumental\n767\t7.24\n768\t6.85\n769\t7.03\n770\t7.01\n771\t6.64\n772\t6.52\n773\tMixing\n774\t7.13\n775\t6.88\n776\t7.07\n777\t6.97\n778\t6.59\n779\t6.38\n780\tStructure\n781\t6.94\n782\t6.83\n783\t6.98\n784\t7.02\n785\t6.55\n786\t6.27\n787\tSongEval\n788\tCoherence\n789\t4.55\n790\t4.28\n791\t4.44\n792\t4.49\n793\t4.33\n794\t4.28\n795\tMusicality\n796\t4.42\n797\t4.12\n798\t4.30\n799\t4.36\n800\t4.19\n801\t4.15\n802\tMemorability\n803\t4.51\n804\t4.27\n805\t4.43\n806\t4.51\n807\t4.29\n808\t4.23\n809\tClarity\n810\t4.45\n811\t4.17\n812\t4.33\n813\t4.37\n814\t4.23\n815\t4.17\n816\tNaturalness\n817\t4.37\n818\t4.10\n819\t4.27\n820\t4.37\n821\t4.16\n822\t4.08\n823\tAudioBox-Aesthetic\n824\tContent Enjoyment\n825\t7.47\n826\t7.35\n827\t7.40\n828\t7.31\n829\t7.39\n830\t7.42\n831\tContent Usefulness\n832\t7.86\n833\t7.85\n834\t7.75\n835\t7.67\n836\t7.82\n837\t7.83\n838\tProduction Complexity\n839\t6.64\n840\t6.67\n841\t6.71\n842\t6.67\n843\t6.64\n844\t6.49\n845\tProduction Quality\n846\t8.15\n847\t8.08\n848\t8.08\n849\t7.95\n850\t8.15\n851\t8.20\n852\tTags Following\n853\tGenre\n854\t8.08\n855\t8.33\n856\t8.28\n857\t8.46\n858\t8.01\n859\t7.60\n860\tMoods\n861\t8.94\n862\t8.93\n863\t8.98\n864\t8.67\n865\t8.57\n866\t8.20\n867\tInstruments\n868\t8.65\n869\t8.80\n870\t8.89\n871\t8.66\n872\t8.15\n873\t7.79\n874\tVocal Gender\n875\t7.85\n876\t7.54\n877\t7.58\n878\t7.77\n879\t7.57\n880\t7.48\n881\tVocal Timbre\n882\t8.68\n883\t8.71\n884\t8.67\n885\t8.38\n886\t8.31\n887\t8.58\n888\tIntelligibility\n889\tPER\n890\t6.10\n891\t4.19\n892\t6.80\n893\t9.04\n894\t6.40\n895\t6.29\n896\tQwen-Music achieves strong performance across musicality and audio-quality metrics.\n897\tAcross SongBench, SongEval, and AudioBox-Aesthetic, it obtains the best result in 13 out of 16 evaluated dimensions.\n898\tOn SongBench, Qwen-Music ranks first in six out of seven dimensions, including melody, arrangement, musicality, vocal quality, instrumental quality, and mixing.\n899\tOn SongEval, it consistently ranks first across all five dimensions: coherence, musicality, memorability, clarity, and naturalness.\n900\tOn AudioBox-Aesthetic, Qwen-Music achieves the best results in content enjoyment and content usefulness while remaining competitive on production-related metrics.\n901\tThese results indicate strong overall generation quality in both composition and rendering.\n902\tQwen-Music also demonstrates competitive controllability and lyric intelligibility.\n903\tOn tag following, it achieves an average score of 8.44 across five control dimensions, within 0.04 points of the best-performing system on average.\n904\tIt performs particularly well on fine-grained vocal control, achieving the best result on vocal gender following and ranking second on both mood and vocal timbre control.\n905\tAlthough Mureka V8 and Suno V5 obtain slightly higher scores on genre and instrument control respectively, Qwen-Music remains competitive across all dimensions, indicating balanced controllability across different musical attributes.\n906\tFor intelligibility, Qwen-Music achieves a PER of 6.10, the second-lowest among all systems.\n907\tOverall, these results show that Qwen-Music offers a strong balance among musicality, audio quality, controllability, and lyric intelligibility.\n908\t4.1.2  Cover Song Generation\n909\tTable 6:  Objective cover song generation results on the AI-generated reference-melody set, containing 100 English and 100 Chinese examples.\n910\tThe Qwen-Music (section) column uses section-level melody conditioning, while the Qwen-Music (unique section) column uses unique-section-level melody conditioning.\n911\tHigher is better except for PER and Melody MAE.\n912\tBest results are shown in  bold , and second-best results are  underlined .\n913\tMetric\n914\tQwen-Music\n915\t(section)\n916\tQwen-Music\n917\t(unique section)\n918\tSuno V5.5\n919\tSuno V5\n920\tMiniMax Cover\n921\tSongBench\n922\tMelody\n923\t6.86\n924\t6.85\n925\t7.13\n926\t7.28\n927\t6.64\n928\tArrangement\n929\t7.27\n930\t7.25\n931\t7.56\n932\t7.61\n933\t6.70\n934\tMusicality\n935\t6.05\n936\t6.04\n937\t6.36\n938\t6.37\n939\t5.72\n940\tVocal\n941\t7.30\n942\t7.29\n943\t7.35\n944\t7.47\n945\t7.14\n946\tInstrumental\n947\t7.31\n948\t7.26\n949\t7.28\n950\t7.34\n951\t6.74\n952\tMixing\n953\t6.96\n954\t6.94\n955\t7.29\n956\t7.33\n957\t6.66\n958\tStructure\n959\t6.83\n960\t6.80\n961\t7.19\n962\t7.27\n963\t6.56\n964\tIntelligibility\n965\tPER (   ↓  \\downarrow   )\n966\t19.28\n967\t17.47\n968\t5.77\n969\t8.46\n970\t25.35\n971\tMelody Following\n972\tMelody MAE (   ↓  \\downarrow   )\n973\t1.48\n974\t1.80\n975\t2.00\n976\t1.87\n977\t1.89\n978\tTag Following\n979\tGenre\n980\t5.92\n981\t7.34\n982\t8.27\n983\t7.14\n984\t5.42\n985\tMood\n986\t7.32\n987\t8.51\n988\t8.77\n989\t7.92\n990\t7.19\n991\tInstruments\n992\t7.55\n993\t8.42\n994\t9.14\n995\t8.35\n996\t7.22\n997\tVocal Gender\n998\t7.96\n999\t8.89\n1000\t9.38\n1001\t9.16\n1002\t6.35\n1003\tVocal Timbre\n1004\t7.77\n1005\t8.69\n1006\t9.23\n1007\t8.53\n1008\t7.88\n1009\tTable 7:  Objective cover song generation results on the real-world popular-song reference-melody set, containing 100 English and 100 Chinese examples.\n1010\tThe Qwen-Music (section) column uses section-level melody conditioning, while the Qwen-Music (unique section) column uses unique-section-level melody conditioning.\n1011\tHigher is better except for PER and Melody MAE.\n1012\tBest results are shown in  bold , and second-best results are  underlined .\n1013\tMetric\n1014\tQwen-Music\n1015\t(section)\n1016\tQwen-Music\n1017\t(unique section)\n1018\tMiniMax Cover\n1019\tSongBench\n1020\tMelody\n1021\t6.55\n1022\t6.57\n1023\t6.18\n1024\tArrangement\n1025\t6.84\n1026\t6.86\n1027\t6.16\n1028\tMusicality\n1029\t5.75\n1030\t5.79\n1031\t5.30\n1032\tVocal\n1033\t7.07\n1034\t7.09\n1035\t6.73\n1036\tInstrumental\n1037\t6.96\n1038\t7.00\n1039\t6.41\n1040\tMixing\n1041\t6.66\n1042\t6.67\n1043\t6.25\n1044\tStructure\n1045\t6.48\n1046\t6.46\n1047\t6.13\n1048\tIntelligibility\n1049\tPER (   ↓  \\downarrow   )\n1050\t20.20\n1051\t18.49\n1052\t22.48\n1053\tMelody Following\n1054\tMelody MAE (   ↓  \\downarrow   )\n1055\t1.44\n1056\t1.80\n1057\t1.76\n1058\tTag Following\n1059\tGenre\n1060\t6.90\n1061\t7.35\n1062\t5.84\n1063\tMood\n1064\t7.48\n1065\t8.05\n1066\t7.05\n1067\tInstruments\n1068\t8.05\n1069\t8.30\n1070\t7.23\n1071\tVocal Gender\n1072\t8.88\n1073\t9.18\n1074\t6.80\n1075\tVocal Timbre\n1076\t8.21\n1077\t8.54\n1078\t7.75\n1079\tWe evaluate cover song generation under reference-melody conditioning.\n1080\tGiven a reference melody, target musical tags, and lyrics, the model is expected to generate a new song that preserves the reference melody while following the requested style and vocal attributes.\n1081\tWe construct two evaluation sets.\n1082\tThe first uses reference songs generated by AI music models, including Suno V5.5 and Mureka V8, with 100 English and 100 Chinese examples.\n1083\tThe second uses real-world popular songs as reference melodies, also with 100 English and 100 Chinese examples.\n1084\tIn the tables,  section-level melody  denotes conditioning with melody tokens for each lyric-bearing section, while  unique-section-level melody  denotes conditioning with one representative melody for each repeated section label.\n1085\tOn the AI-generated reference set (Table   6  ), section-level Melody-CoT achieves the lowest Melody MAE, indicating stronger direct reference-melody cloning, while unique-section-level conditioning substantially improves tag following over the section-level mode.\n1086\tCommercial systems remain strong on several general musicality and tag-following metrics.\n1087\tOn the real-world popular-song set (Table   7  ), Qwen-Music outperforms MiniMax Cover across most objective dimensions.\n1088\tThe unique-section-level mode yields better musicality, intelligibility, and tag following on most metrics, whereas the section-level mode gives the best direct melody following.\n1089\tThese results show that the two Melody-CoT modes provide complementary control trade-offs for cover song generation.\n1090\t4.2  Evaluation of Qwen-Music-Render\n1091\tQwen-Music-Render performs generative rendering from Music Semantic Tokens and the rewritten textual condition into high-fidelity 48 kHz stereo waveforms.\n1092\tThis section evaluates two key aspects of this rendering module.\n1093\tWe first study the DiT rendering pipeline, focusing on the effects of rewritten textual conditioning, CFG strategy, and latent backbone choice.\n1094\tWe then evaluate whether the Band-Mode Refiner improves acoustic reconstruction quality when paired with Spec-VAE.\n1095\tOverall, the results show that rewritten textual conditioning with  text-drop  CFG gives the strongest generation quality, and that the refiner consistently improves spectral, mel-scale, and stereo reconstruction metrics.\n1096\t4.2.1  Effect of Text Conditioning and CFG in DiT Rendering\n1097\tTable   8   studies three design choices in the DiT rendering pipeline: the latent backbone used as the prediction target, the rewritten textual condition provided to the renderer, and the null-branch design used for classifier-free guidance (CFG).\n1098\t“None” indicates no text conditioning, while frame-aligned LM token conditioning is still provided.\n1099\tThe results show that rewritten textual conditioning provides useful guidance beyond the song-level scaffold carried by LM tokens: under the matched Spec-VAE + LM-token drop setting, musical tags improve over no-text conditioning, and adding lyrics further improves most metrics.\n1100\tAmong CFG variants,  Text-drop  CFG achieves the best overall performance, supporting our design choice in Section   2.4.1  : LM tokens should be retained as the primary rendering scaffold, while musical tags and lyrics serve as complementary semantic guidance.\n1101\tUnder matched text-conditioning and CFG settings, Spec-VAE also generally outperforms Levo 2 VAE  (Lei  et al. ,  2026b ) , indicating that a stronger latent representation leads to better final rendering quality.\n1102\tOverall, the best configuration combines  Spec-VAE, musical tags + lyrics, and  Text-drop  CFG .\n1103\tTable 8:  DiT rendering ablation on our bilingual EN/ZH set (100 samples each).\n1104\tWe compare latent backbones, rewritten textual conditioning, and CFG null-branch designs.\n1105\tFor fair comparison, Spec-VAE results here bypass the Band-Mode Refiner.\n1106\t“None” indicates no text conditioning, while frame-aligned LM token conditioning is always provided.\n1107\tText-drop ,  Full-drop , and  LM-token-drop  respectively remove text conditioning only, both text and LM token conditioning, and LM token conditioning only from the null branch.\n1108\tBest results are highlighted in  bold , and second-best results are  underlined .\n1109\tLatent Backbone\n1110\tLevo 2 VAE\n1111\tLevo 2 VAE\n1112\tSpec-VAE\n1113\tSpec-VAE\n1114\tSpec-VAE\n1115\tSpec-VAE\n1116\tText Conditioning\n1117\tNone\n1118\tTags + Lyrics\n1119\tTags only\n1120\tTags + Lyrics\n1121\tTags + Lyrics\n1122\tTags + Lyrics\n1123\tCFG Strategy\n1124\tLM-token drop\n1125\tLM-token drop\n1126\tLM-token drop\n1127\tFull-drop\n1128\tLM-token drop\n1129\tText-drop\n1130\tSongBench\n1131\tMelody\n1132\t6.55\n1133\t6.56\n1134\t6.88\n1135\t6.89\n1136\t6.88\n1137\t6.96\n1138\tArrangement\n1139\t6.87\n1140\t6.88\n1141\t7.15\n1142\t7.17\n1143\t7.17\n1144\t7.25\n1145\tMusicality\n1146\t5.66\n1147\t5.71\n1148\t6.04\n1149\t6.05\n1150\t6.04\n1151\t6.17\n1152\tVocal\n1153\t6.80\n1154\t6.88\n1155\t7.21\n1156\t7.29\n1157\t7.30\n1158\t7.37\n1159\tInstrumental\n1160\t6.96\n1161\t6.95\n1162\t7.08\n1163\t7.20\n1164\t7.19\n1165\t7.21\n1166\tMixing\n1167\t6.55\n1168\t6.59\n1169\t6.89\n1170\t7.02\n1171\t7.02\n1172\t7.01\n1173\tStructure\n1174\t6.36\n1175\t6.38\n1176\t6.69\n1177\t6.75\n1178\t6.75\n1179\t6.83\n1180\tSongEval\n1181\tCoherence\n1182\t4.28\n1183\t4.31\n1184\t4.44\n1185\t4.38\n1186\t4.39\n1187\t4.47\n1188\tMusicality\n1189\t4.11\n1190\t4.17\n1191\t4.28\n1192\t4.25\n1193\t4.25\n1194\t4.34\n1195\tMemorability\n1196\t4.18\n1197\t4.24\n1198\t4.38\n1199\t4.33\n1200\t4.33\n1201\t4.42\n1202\tClarity\n1203\t4.14\n1204\t4.20\n1205\t4.33\n1206\t4.29\n1207\t4.29\n1208\t4.37\n1209\tNaturalness\n1210\t4.05\n1211\t4.10\n1212\t4.22\n1213\t4.18\n1214\t4.18\n1215\t4.26\n1216\t4.2.2  Does the Band-Mode Refiner Improve Acoustic Reconstruction?\n1217\tWe next isolate the acoustic decoder from LM generation and evaluate whether the Band-Mode Refiner improves reconstruction fidelity.\n1218\tSpec-VAE and Spec-VAE + Refiner are evaluated on the full 546 tracks from the Song Describer Dataset  (Manco  et al. ,  2023 ) , together with four recent open-source audio VAE systems:    ε  \\varepsilon   ar-VAE  (Wang and others,  2025 ) , Stable Audio Open (SA-Open)  (Evans  et al. ,  2024 ) , Levo 2  (Lei  et al. ,  2026b ) , and SAME-L  (Parker  et al. ,  2026 ) .\n1219\tAll systems are evaluated at their native operating conditions.\n1220\tWe report the baseline ( Spec-VAE ) and the full pipeline with Band-Mode Refiner ( Spec-VAE + Refiner ) separately to isolate the contribution of the refiner.\n1221\tMetrics\n1222\tWe measure reconstruction quality along three axes: spectral fidelity, mel-scale frequency response, and stereo image preservation.  (1) Spectral reconstruction:  We use SI-SDR (dB,    ↑  \\uparrow   )  (Le Roux  et al. ,  2019 ) , STFT Distance (   ↓  \\downarrow   ), and STFT      log1p   {}_{\\text{log1p}}    (   ↓  \\downarrow   ) to measure time-domain fidelity, broadband spectral deviation, and low-amplitude spectral details.  (2) Mel reconstruction:  We use Mel Distance (   ↓  \\downarrow   ) and MEL      log1p   {}_{\\text{log1p}}    (   ↓  \\downarrow   ) to evaluate reconstruction quality on a perceptually spaced frequency axis.  (3) Stereo image quality:\n1223\tWe use CCPC (Cross-Channel Phase Coherence;       ∈   [  0  ,  1  ]    \\in[0,1]   ,    ↑  \\uparrow   )  (Wang and others,  2025 )  and Spectral Pan Error (   ↓  \\downarrow   ). CCPC evaluates inter-channel phase coherence, while Spectral Pan Error measures the L1 distance in the frequency-wise stereo pan profile      pan  ​   (  f  )    =     |   L  ​   (  f  )    |   2   /   (     |   L  ​   (  f  )    |   2   +    |   R  ​   (  f  )    |   2    )     \\text{pan}(f)=|L(f)|^{2}/(|L(f)|^{2}+|R(f)|^{2})     (Avendano and Jot,  2002 ) .\n1224\tTable 9:\n1225\tObjective reconstruction quality on the Song Describer Dataset.\n1226\tAll models are evaluated at their native operating conditions.\n1227\tSubscript values denote 95% confidence intervals computed over the per-file metrics.\n1228\tBest results are highlighted in  bold , and second-best results are  underlined .\n1229\tMetric\n1230\tϵ  \\epsilon    ar-VAE\n1231\tSA-Open\n1232\tLevo 2\n1233\tSAME-L\n1234\tSpec-VAE\n1235\tSpec-VAE\n1236\t+Refiner\n1237\tSTFT-Scale Reconstruction\n1238\tSI-SDR    ↑  \\uparrow\n1239\t12.4     ±  \\pm   0.4\n1240\t6.7    ±  \\pm   0.3\n1241\t8.1    ±  \\pm   0.3\n1242\t12.5     ±  \\pm   0.4\n1243\t10.9    ±  \\pm   0.4\n1244\t11.3    ±  \\pm   0.4\n1245\tSTFT Dist    ↓  \\downarrow\n1246\t0.880     ±  \\pm   0.014\n1247\t1.016    ±  \\pm   0.016\n1248\t0.971    ±  \\pm   0.016\n1249\t0.986    ±  \\pm   0.015\n1250\t0.916    ±  \\pm   0.016\n1251\t0.870     ±  \\pm   0.014\n1252\tSTFT      log1p   {}_{\\text{log1p}}       ↓  \\downarrow\n1253\t0.079    ±  \\pm   0.005\n1254\t0.089    ±  \\pm   0.005\n1255\t0.086    ±  \\pm   0.005\n1256\t0.079    ±  \\pm   0.005\n1257\t0.078     ±  \\pm   0.005\n1258\t0.075     ±  \\pm   0.005\n1259\tMel-Scale Reconstruction\n1260\tMel Dist    ↓  \\downarrow\n1261\t0.509     ±  \\pm   0.008\n1262\t0.612    ±  \\pm   0.007\n1263\t0.599    ±  \\pm   0.008\n1264\t0.539    ±  \\pm   0.010\n1265\t0.572    ±  \\pm   0.010\n1266\t0.461     ±  \\pm   0.006\n1267\tMEL      log1p   {}_{\\text{log1p}}       ↓  \\downarrow\n1268\t0.095    ±  \\pm   0.006\n1269\t0.106    ±  \\pm   0.006\n1270\t0.103    ±  \\pm   0.006\n1271\t0.096    ±  \\pm   0.006\n1272\t0.093     ±  \\pm   0.006\n1273\t0.089     ±  \\pm   0.005\n1274\tStereo Image Quality\n1275\tCCPC    ↑  \\uparrow\n1276\t0.973     ±  \\pm   0.003\n1277\t0.933    ±  \\pm   0.004\n1278\t0.947    ±  \\pm   0.004\n1279\t0.970     ±  \\pm   0.003\n1280\t0.966    ±  \\pm   0.003\n1281\t0.973     ±  \\pm   0.002\n1282\tSpectral Pan Err    ↓  \\downarrow\n1283\t0.267     ±  \\pm   0.004\n1284\t0.276    ±  \\pm   0.004\n1285\t0.273    ±  \\pm   0.004\n1286\t0.276    ±  \\pm   0.004\n1287\t0.268    ±  \\pm   0.004\n1288\t0.264     ±  \\pm   0.004\n1289\tResults\n1290\tTable   9   summarizes the reconstruction results.\n1291\tThe full rendering decoder ( Spec-VAE + Refiner ) achieves the best STFT Distance (0.870), STFT      log1p   {}_{\\text{log1p}}    (0.075), Mel Distance (0.461), MEL      log1p   {}_{\\text{log1p}}    (0.089), and Spectral Pan Error (0.264), while matching the best CCPC score of 0.973.\n1292\tCompared with Spec-VAE alone, the refiner improves all reported metrics, with the largest gain on Mel Distance (0.572 to 0.461).\n1293\tThese results support the band-specific correction strategy and show that the refiner improves perceptual frequency response and stereo spatial fidelity without sacrificing overall reconstruction quality.\n1294\t5  Conclusion\n1295\tIn this report, we presented Qwen-Music, a unified large-scale music generation system for both text-to-music generation and reference-melody-based cover song generation.\n1296\tQwen-Music connects semantic-level composition with high-fidelity audio synthesis through three core components:  Qwen-Music-Tokenizer , which represents music as compact 25 Hz single-codebook Music Semantic Tokens;  Qwen-Music-LLM , which performs melody-aware autoregressive music modeling with a Melody-CoT mechanism; and  Qwen-Music-Render , which performs generative stereo rendering from both Music Semantic Tokens and rewritten textual conditions.\n1297\tTogether, these components enable controllable full-song generation with coherent lyrics, stable musical structure, realistic vocals, and high-fidelity stereo waveforms.\n1298\tTo train this system at scale, we introduced a  quality-graded pre-training curriculum  over more than 5 million hours of multilingual music data, allowing Qwen-Music-LLM to first learn broad musical coverage and then progressively refine generation quality.\n1299\tWe further adopted a  multi-stage post-training alignment  pipeline that combines supervised learning, iterative offline DPO, and online GSPO, improving musicality, instruction following, and controllability.\n1300\tFor Qwen-Music-Render, acoustic quality filtering provides reliable high-fidelity supervision for 48 kHz stereo rendering.\n1301\tExtensive evaluations demonstrate that Qwen-Music achieves strong performance across subjective preference studies, genre-wise Bradley–Terry analysis, external leaderboard comparison, and objective metrics.\n1302\tIn text-to-music generation, Qwen-Music shows competitive or superior performance against leading proprietary systems in musicality, audio quality, controllability, and lyric intelligibility.\n1303\tIn cover song generation, it demonstrates strong reference-melody preservation and stylistic adaptation, while render-specific evaluations confirm the benefits of rewritten textual conditioning, text-drop CFG, and Band-Mode Refiner for high-fidelity stereo reconstruction.\n1304\tQwen-Music represents a step toward unified, scalable, and controllable music generation systems that bridge long-range musical semantics and waveform-level acoustic realization.\n1305\tFuture work will explore more flexible long-context musical structure modeling, finer-grained expressive control over singing and performance, and more efficient rendering architectures for high-quality music generation.\n1306\tReferences\n1307\tA. Agostinelli, T. I. Denk, Z. Borsos, J. Engel, M. Verzetti, A. Caillon, Q. Huang, A. Jansen, A. Roberts, M. Tagliasacchi,  et al.  (2023)\n1308\tMusiclm: generating music from text .\n1309\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2301.11325 .\n1310\tCited by:   §1  .\n1311\tC. Avendano and J. Jot (2002)\n1312\tFrequency domain techniques for stereo to multichannel upmix .\n1313\tIn  AES 22nd International Conference on Virtual, Synthetic and Entertainment Audio ,\n1314\tCited by:   §4.2.2  .\n1315\tK. Chen, Y. Wu, H. Liu, M. Nezhurina, T. Berg-Kirkpatrick, and S. Dubnov (2024)\n1316\tMusicLDM: enhancing novelty in text-to-music generation using beat-synchronous mixup strategies .\n1317\tIn  ICASSP 2024-2024 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP) ,\n1318\tpp. 1206–1210 .\n1319\tCited by:   §1  .\n1320\tC. Chiu, J. Qin, Y. Zhang, J. Yu, and Y. Wu (2022)\n1321\tSelf-supervised learning with random-projection quantizer for speech recognition .\n1322\tIn  Proceedings of the 39th International Conference on Machine Learning ,   K. Chaudhuri, S. Jegelka, L. Song, C. Szepesvari, G. Niu, and S. Sabato (Eds.) ,\n1323\tProceedings of Machine Learning Research , Vol.  162 ,   pp. 3915–3924 .\n1324\tExternal Links:   Link ,\n1325\t2